  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "HowTo",
  name: "How to Set Up an African Grey Parrot Cage",
  description: "A breeder's step-by-step blueprint for setting up an African Grey cage: choose the cage, add zoned perches, add rotating toys, set food and water stations, and place the cage.",
  step: howToSteps.map((s, i) => ({ "@type": "HowToStep", position: i + 1, name: s.name, text: s.text })),
};

// heading classes — match Roys/homepage parity (font-lora, text-logo-dark, no text-3xl)
const h2 = "font-lora font-bold text-logo-dark leading-tight mb-4 mt-2 scroll-mt-24";
const h3 = "font-lora font-semibold text-xl text-logo-dark mb-3 mt-6";
const h4 = "font-lora font-semibold text-lg text-logo-dark mb-2 mt-5";
const h5 = "font-lora font-semibold text-base text-logo-dark mt-5 mb-1";
const h6 = "font-sora font-semibold text-xs uppercase tracking-wide mt-4 mb-1";
const p = "text-stone-700 leading-relaxed mb-4";
const lnk = "underline font-medium";
const figc = "block text-center text-sm text-stone-500 mt-2";
---

<BaseLayout {title} {description} {canonical} ogType="article" hideGlobalCta heroPreload="/african-grey-cage-setup-blueprint-infographic.webp">
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(articleSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(howToSchema)} />

  <style>
    .cage-d .cag-seam { display:flex; align-items:center; gap:26px; max-width:1100px; margin:2.25rem auto 1.5rem; padding:0 24px; }
    .cage-d .cag-seam__line { flex:1; height:1px; background:rgba(45,106,79,.16); }
    .cage-d .cag-seam img { height:30px; width:auto; display:block; opacity:.92; flex-shrink:0; }
    @media (max-width:600px){ .cage-d .cag-seam { gap:16px; } .cage-d .cag-seam img { height:24px; } }
    .cage-d .cage-hero h1 { font-size:clamp(1.7rem, 1.1rem + 2.6vw, 2.4rem) !important; line-height:1.14 !important; }
    .cage-d figure img { box-shadow:0 10px 30px rgba(60,30,10,.08); }
  </style>

  <div class="cage-d">
    <div style="max-width:1200px;margin:0 auto;">
      <Breadcrumb items={breadcrumbs} />
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Hero -->
    <section class="cage-hero text-white px-4 pt-12 pb-10" style="background:#2D6A4F">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
          <div>
            <p class="font-sora text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-3" style="color:#f3a18f">Care Guide · Breeder Blueprint · Midland, TX</p>
            <h1 class="font-lora font-bold mb-4" style="color:#faf7f4">African Grey Cage Setup: The Breeder's Blueprint</h1>
            <p class="text-lg mb-6" style="color:rgba(250,247,244,0.85)">Not a generic checklist — the exact cage we send every C.A.Gs chick home to. Size, zone-by-zone layout, perch variety, toy rotation, food, sleep and the mistakes that quietly cause plucking.</p>
            <a href="/available/" class="inline-block bg-clay text-white font-sora font-semibold px-7 py-3" style="border-radius:50px">See available African Greys</a>
          </div>
          <figure class="m-0">
            <img src="/african-grey-cage-setup-blueprint-infographic.webp" width="1280" height="698" alt="The breeder blueprint for the ultimate African Grey cage setup, showing spatial requirements, layered perching strategy, enrichment, nutrition, safety and UV lighting" class="w-full rounded-2xl" fetchpriority="high" />
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 2. Top lead-capture strip -->
    <div style="max-width:1100px;margin:0 auto;" class="px-4 -mt-6 relative z-10">
      <InquiryCompact heading="Building a cage and not sure it's right?" subtext="Send us a photo of your setup — we'll tell you what to fix before your Grey comes home." subject="Cage setup question" page="blog/cage-setup" idPrefix="top" />
    </div>

    <!-- 3. Jump nav (desktop + mobile horizontal scroll) -->
    <div style="max-width:900px;margin:1.25rem auto 0;" class="px-4">
      <JumpNav links={jumpLinks} sticky={false} />
    </div>

    <section class="px-4 pt-8 pb-4" style="background:#faf7f4">
      <div style="max-width:760px;margin:0 auto;">

        <!-- 4. Quick-Answer box (TOP special-element) -->
        <div id="quick" class="scroll-mt-24">
          <QuickAnswer title="African Grey Cage Setup at a Glance" rows={quickRows} headingLevel="h2" />
        </div>

        <p class={p}>Most cage problems trace back to one thing: a cage chosen for the owner's budget instead of the bird's biology. Get the blueprint below right — size, zones, perches, toys, materials and placement — and the cage stops being a trigger for <a href="/blog/african-grey-health-problems/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228">feather plucking and screaming</a> and starts being a home your Grey actually thrives in.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-parrot-in-cage-setup-room.webp" width="1100" height="628" alt="African Grey parrot perched in a well-lit room beside a properly set-up cage with toys and food bowls" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>

        <!-- 5. Cage size -->
        <h2 id="size" class={h2}>What Size Cage Does an African Grey Need?</h2>
        <p class={p}>The short answer, snippet-ready: an African Grey needs a cage at least <strong>36–48 inches wide, 24–36 inches deep, and 48–60 inches tall</strong> — and larger is strongly recommended. A Congo needs more room than a Timneh, and in both cases width matters more than height, because Greys move side-to-side far more than they climb.</p>

        <ComparisonTable columns={setupCols} rows={setupRows} verdict="Buy the widest cage your room allows — we have never once heard an owner say their Grey's cage was too big." />

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-cage-size-dimensions-diagram.webp" width="760" height="760" alt="Annotated diagram of an extra-large African Grey cage showing height, width, depth, bar spacing and seed-guard dimensions" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>Typical extra-large play-top dimensions — use it as a floor, not a ceiling.</span>
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Congo African Grey Cage Size</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Minimum vs Ideal Dimensions</h4>
        <p class={p}>A Congo is a powerful, full-sized parrot. The 36"×24"×48" minimum just clears full wing extension; a <strong>40"×30"×60"</strong> cage is the standard we build around in our own aviary.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Why a bigger cage prevents feather plucking</h5>
        <p class={p}>Confinement stress is real — a Grey with no room to flap or forage turns that energy inward, and the chest and leg feathers are the first to go. Space is the cheapest enrichment you will ever buy.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Our aviary flight-space benchmark</h6>
        <p class={p}>Every chick we raise grows up with daily out-of-cage flight time on top of a large enclosure. We tell families to treat the cage as a secure base camp — a few hours of supervised freedom daily does more for behaviour than any single accessory.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Timneh African Grey Cage Size</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>How Timneh Sizing &amp; Bar Spacing Differ</h4>
        <p class={p}>Timnehs run smaller, so 30"×20"×40" clears the minimum — though many owners happily size up. The bigger difference is bar spacing.</p>
        <ComparisonTable columns={sizeCols} rows={sizeRows} verdict="If your Grey can push its head between the bars, the spacing is unsafe — full stop." />
        <h5 class={h5}>Safe bar spacing, by age and subspecies</h5>
        <p class={p}>Congos: 3/4"–1". Timnehs: 5/8"–3/4". For a just-weaned fledgling we default to <strong>7/8"–1"</strong> until it is fully sure-footed — a clumsy young bird is far more likely to catch a wing than a steady adult.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">The head-entrapment test</h6>
        <p class={p}>Forget the cage's marketing size class. A "large bird" cage built for macaws often runs 1.25"–1.5" spacing — wide enough for a Grey to slip its head through. Always check the spacing number, never just the size label.</p>

        <Callout variant="mistake" title="The size mistake that causes plucking">
          <p>Buying a tall, narrow "tower" cage because it looks generous in a small footprint. Greys need horizontal room to move, not height they rarely use. Prioritise width every time.</p>
        </Callout>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 6. Zone layout -->
        <h2 id="zones" class={h2}>The Best Cage Layout: Zone It Like a Breeder</h2>
        <p class={p}>Here is the differentiator almost no competitor teaches: don't fill a cage evenly — <strong>zone it</strong>. A parrot reads its cage in three layers, and matching each zone to its natural behaviour is what turns a box of bars into a setup your Grey uses all day.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-cage-zones-parrot-perspective.webp" width="500" height="416" alt="A parrot's perspective of cage zones: the top two-thirds is premium resting and activity space, the bottom third is for foraging" class="w-full max-w-md mx-auto rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>A Grey spends most of its day in the top two-thirds and forages in the bottom third.</span>
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Upper Zone — Security &amp; Sleep</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>The Sleeping Perch</h4>
        <p class={p}>Birds feel safest up high, so the top of the cage is for resting and sleep. Put the highest, most comfortable perch here — ideally a rope perch that is gentle on joints — and keep this zone calm.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>How many hours of sleep an African Grey needs</h5>
        <p class={p}>Greys need <strong>10–12 hours</strong> of quiet, dark sleep. Cover the cage or use a dedicated sleep cage in a separate quiet room; chronic sleep deprivation drives the same plucking and biting that owners blame on "attitude."</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Middle Zone — Eating &amp; Interaction</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Food &amp; Water Placement</h4>
        <p class={p}>The middle is the social, working zone — this is where food and water bowls, the main activity perch, and most toys belong, at the bird's eye level where it spends interactive time.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Never place a bowl under a perch</h5>
        <p class={p}>It sounds obvious, yet it is the most common contamination mistake: a bowl directly below a perch collects droppings. Offset bowls horizontally from perches, and use stainless rather than chewable plastic.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Lower Zone — Foraging &amp; Climbing</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Ground-Level Foraging</h4>
        <p class={p}>The bottom third is for foraging and climbing. Scatter foraging toys and a low foraging tray here so your Grey works for treats the way it would in the wild — the single best boredom-buster you can build in.</p>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 7. Perches -->
        <h2 id="perches" class={h2}>How to Set Up the Perches</h2>
        <p class={p}>Perches are where your Grey stands every waking hour, so monotony here does real damage. Provide at least three — ideally four to seven across the zones — and deliberately vary diameter and texture.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-perch-setup-guide-infographic.webp" width="760" height="1327" alt="The 3-perch variety setup for African Greys: natural wood, soft rope and textured conditioning perches, with placement and safety rules" class="w-full max-w-md mx-auto rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Natural Wood, Rope &amp; Conditioning Perches</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Diameter &amp; Placement Variety</h4>
        <p class={p}>The working trio: a natural-wood perch (1"–1.5", for daytime), a rope perch (softer, for the sleep zone), and a pumice or concrete conditioning perch placed low for nails and beak. Mount them at different heights, and never directly above a bowl.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Why smooth dowels cause pressure sores</h5>
        <p class={p}>The round dowels that ship with most cages are a uniform diameter and slick — the foot grips identically all day, and within months that constant pressure point can ulcerate into bumblefoot. Treat the included dowel as packaging, not a perch.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Manzanita vs java wood — our pick</h6>
        <p class={p}>We favour manzanita for its rock-hard, irregular surface that resists chewing and conditions feet; java wood is a great second choice with more sculptural branching to climb. Both are non-toxic and built to last.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Perches to Avoid</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Sandpaper Covers &amp; Plastic</h4>
        <p class={p}>Skip sandpaper perch covers entirely — they abrade the foot without ever conditioning nails, and they cause the very sores owners hope to prevent. Plastic perches are slick and offer no enrichment. Wood, rope and natural mineral surfaces only.</p>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 8. Toys & enrichment -->
        <h2 id="toys" class={h2}>The Best Toys &amp; Enrichment Setup</h2>
        <p class={p}>An African Grey has the cognition of a young child. A cage full of toys it has already solved is, to a Grey, an empty cage — and a bored Grey is a plucking, screaming Grey. The fix is not more toys; it is the right mix, zoned and rotated.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-cage-toy-enrichment-guide.webp" width="760" height="983" alt="How to arrange bird toys inside the cage for maximum enrichment: divide into zones, avoid overcrowding, match toys to personality, rotate weekly, and prioritise safety" class="w-full max-w-md mx-auto rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Chew Toys</h3>
        <p class={p}>Greys are relentless chewers, so soft-wood blocks, palm and cork toys are non-negotiable — destruction is the point, and a shredded toy is a job well done. Refresh these as they are demolished.</p>
        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-wooden-chew-toys.webp" width="760" height="505" alt="A colorful wooden block chew toy hanging inside an African Grey cage" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Puzzle &amp; Foraging Toys</h3>
        <p class={p}>Puzzle toys with latches, locks and stacking parts engage a Grey's problem-solving brain, while foraging toys that hide food make the bird work for every bite. As the <a href="https://parrots.org/encyclopedia/grey-parrot/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">World Parrot Trust's grey parrot profile ↗</a> documents, wild Greys spend much of the day foraging across the canopy — so foraging is the most mentally stimulating category of all, and the one that belongs in the lower zone.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>The Weekly Rotation System</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>The 2–3 Swap Rule</h4>
        <p class={p}>Here is the tension: Greys are <strong>neophobic</strong> — they distrust brand-new objects — yet bored of familiar ones within a week. So keep a bin of 6–8 toys and every 5–7 days rotate out 2–3 while leaving 2 trusted toys as anchors.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Foraging, shreddable, puzzle &amp; foot toys</h5>
        <p class={p}>Rotate across all four categories so the whole brain stays engaged: <strong>foraging</strong> (work for food), <strong>shreddable</strong> (chewing drive), <strong>puzzle</strong> (cognition), and small <strong>foot</strong> toys to manipulate.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Our weekly rotation schedule</h6>
        <p class={p}>In our aviary every bird gets fresh foraging daily and a 2–3 toy swap weekly, with shreddables refreshed as destroyed. New families get this exact schedule written down when a chick goes home.</p>

        <BreederNote>
          <p>The owners who never deal with plucking aren't the ones who spent the most — they're the ones who kept their Grey's day <em>interesting</em>. Space, zoning, and a rotation habit beat an expensive cage stuffed with stale toys every single time. That's the whole secret, and it's nearly free.</p>
        </BreederNote>

        <!-- 9. Materials -->
        <h2 id="materials" class={h2}>Safe Cage Materials: Stainless vs Powder-Coat</h2>
        <p class={p}>African Greys chew their bars constantly, so your bird effectively eats a little of the cage every day. That turns material choice into a toxicology question — and the answer is mostly stainless steel.</p>
        <h3 class={h3}>Stainless vs Powder-Coated Steel</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Verifying Lead-Free / Zinc-Free</h4>
        <p class={p}><strong>304-grade stainless</strong> is the gold standard — inert, rust-proof, a once-in-a-bird's-life purchase across 40–60 years. Powder-coated steel is acceptable and cheaper, but only if the maker confirms, in writing, that the coating is lead-free and zinc-free.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Metals that can kill your Grey</h5>
        <p class={p}>Galvanized wire (common in hardware-store "flight cages") is zinc-coated, and chrome plating flakes over time. Both are dangerous to a species that gnaws metal for fun — avoid them entirely.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Signs of heavy-metal toxicity — and when to call a vet</h6>
        <p class={p}>Sudden appetite loss, regurgitation, unusual thirst, weakness or seizures can all signal zinc or lead poisoning. It moves fast; any combination is an emergency. Contact a board-certified avian vet immediately — the <a href="https://www.aav.org/search/custom.asp?id=1803" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Association of Avian Veterinarians directory ↗</a> can help you find one — because it is treatable when caught early.</p>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 10. Placement -->
        <h2 id="placement" class={h2}>Where Should You Place the Cage?</h2>
        <p class={p}>Placement is the most-ignored part of cage setup and one of the most important. Push the cage against at least one wall so your Grey isn't exposed on all sides, set the top near your eye level, and put it where the action is.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-corner-cage-setup-real.webp" width="640" height="853" alt="A real African Grey corner cage with a play top set against a wall in a family room, behind a safety gate" class="w-full max-w-sm mx-auto rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>Wall-backed, in a busy room, at eye level — a setup a Grey feels secure in.</span>
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Near Family Activity</h3>
        <p class={p}>Greys are intensely social and need to watch daily life. A cage marooned in a spare room breeds the isolation that drives screaming and plucking. The living room or a home office usually wins.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Away From the Kitchen</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>PTFE / Teflon Fumes</h4>
        <p class={p}>Never place a cage in or beside the kitchen. Overheated non-stick cookware releases PTFE (Teflon) fumes that are odourless to us and lethal to birds within minutes.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Away From Drafts &amp; Windows</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Light, Sun &amp; UVB</h4>
        <p class={p}>Keep the cage clear of drafty doors, AC and heating vents, and more than a few hours of direct sun (which can overheat a bird with no shade). Natural light is good; baking behind glass is not.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Bird-safe UVB lighting</h5>
        <p class={p}>Because window glass filters out UVB, indoor Greys miss the wavelengths they need to make vitamin D3 and use calcium properly. A bird-safe UVB lamp on a timer for a few hours a day supplements that — it does not replace good diet or vet care, but it helps prevent the calcium issues Greys are prone to.</p>

        <figure class="my-7">
          <p class="font-sora font-semibold text-sm uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500 text-center mb-3">Real African Grey setups</p>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-3">
            <img src="/african-grey-dome-cage-setup.webp" width="560" height="560" alt="A tall black dome-top African Grey cage well stocked with toys" class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
            <img src="/african-grey-play-gym-enrichment.webp" width="557" height="960" alt="An African Grey on a large wooden play gym covered in rope and shred toys" class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
            <img src="/african-grey-double-flight-cage.webp" width="500" height="375" alt="A wide double African Grey flight cage filled with rope perches and toys" class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
            <img src="/african-grey-play-top-cage.webp" width="500" height="375" alt="The play-top of an African Grey cage with hanging toys and perches" class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </figure>

        <Callout variant="tip" title="A 10-second placement test">
          <p>Sit where the cage will go. Can the bird see the family come and go, but also retreat to a wall at its back? If yes, you've found the spot. If it would be marooned in the open or hidden away alone, keep looking.</p>
        </Callout>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 11. Mistakes + decision tree (MIDDLE special-element) -->
        <h2 id="mistakes" class={h2}>Common African Grey Cage Setup Mistakes</h2>
        <p class={p}>Most setups fail the same handful of ways. If your build avoids these, you are already ahead of most owners — and most sellers.</p>
        <h3 class={h3}>Too Small or Round</h3>
        <p class={p}>Round cages give a bird no corner to feel secure in and waste usable space; undersized cages are the root of confinement stress. Go rectangular, go wide.</p>
        <h3 class={h3}>Overcrowded With Toys</h3>
        <p class={p}>A wall-to-wall toy jungle leaves no room to flap and can stress or even injure a bird. Leave open flight space — fewer toys, rotated, beats a crowded cage.</p>
        <h3 class={h3}>Poor Perch Placement</h3>
        <p class={p}>Bowls under perches, a single uniform dowel, or every perch crammed at one height — each undoes the zoning you just built. Spread perches across the zones and keep food clear of droppings.</p>

